Be careful not to injure yourself.

32
00:02:08,761 --> 00:02:09,662
That's right.

33
00:02:09,796 --> 00:02:11,231
-Okay.
-Keep control.

34
00:02:11,297 --> 00:02:12,232
Right!

35
00:02:12,499 --> 00:02:14,534
-Let's go.
-All right!

36
00:02:17,737 --> 00:02:19,539
<i>Among the staff watching over the members,</i>

37
00:02:20,473 --> 00:02:23,610
<i>are four young,
nervous-looking individuals.</i>

38
00:02:25,712 --> 00:02:27,013
{\an8}STAGE FACILITATOR
MASAHIRO UEDA (AGE 27)

39
00:02:27,080 --> 00:02:31,518
{\an8}<i>Making sure the concert runs smoothly
and on time is a rookie stage facilitator,</i>

40
00:02:31,584 --> 00:02:33,052
{\an8}<i>Masahiro Ueda.</i>

41
00:02:34,254 --> 00:02:35,588
{\an8}SPECIAL EFFECTS
MICHIRU YABE (AGE 21)

42
00:02:35,655 --> 00:02:39,993
{\an8}<i>Lighting up the arena with special effects
is the youngest member of the team,</i>

43
00:02:40,460 --> 00:02:41,828
{\an8}<i>Michiru Yabe.</i>

44
00:02:42,795 --> 00:02:44,030
{\an8}SOUND
TAKUMA KURAMOCHI (AGE 22)

45
00:02:44,097 --> 00:02:46,733
{\an8}<i>Working in sound,
the key feature of a concert,</i>

46
00:02:46,799 --> 00:02:51,004
{\an8}<i>as his first time being the stage chief
is Takuma Kuramochi.</i>

47
00:02:51,337 --> 00:02:52,872
{\an8}SPECIAL MECHANICS
SHOICHIRO FUKUDA (AGE 24)

48
00:02:52,939 --> 00:02:56,809
{\an8}<i>Operating complex stage equipment
in special mechanics,</i>

49
00:02:57,143 --> 00:02:58,845
{\an8}<i>is Shoichiro Fukuda.</i>

50
00:03:00,713 --> 00:03:05,185
<i>They each have different job descriptions
and positions, but what they share</i>

51
00:03:05,485 --> 00:03:09,989
{\an8}<i>is the desire to give the fans
the time of their life.</i>

52
00:03:12,125 --> 00:03:16,162
{\an8}<i>The duration of the Hey! Say! JUMP tour
is about five months.</i>

53
00:03:16,696 --> 00:03:21,034
<i>Even rookies are expected to
work like professionals.</i>

54
00:03:22,135 --> 00:03:23,503
-Hey.
-Yes.

55
00:03:23,570 --> 00:03:25,205
-Come here right now.
-Yes.

56
00:03:25,738 --> 00:03:28,641
I feel like I could've done more.

57
00:03:29,842 --> 00:03:31,077
But it's difficult.

58
00:03:31,377 --> 00:03:33,646
I'm constantly exhausted.

59
00:03:34,380 --> 00:03:36,916
I don't have a clear picture
of the end result,

60
00:03:37,383 --> 00:03:38,484
so I'm very worried.

61
00:03:39,219 --> 00:03:40,787
It's spilling.

62
00:03:42,021 --> 00:03:45,158
There's been some trouble,
so that has set us back.

63
00:03:45,959 --> 00:03:49,195
I've never been this nervous before.

64
00:03:50,463 --> 00:03:54,534
<i>The flashy world of entertainment
sells dreams to its consumers.</i>

65
00:03:55,568 --> 00:03:58,638
<i>But it's a harsh world behind the scenes.</i>

66
00:04:00,373 --> 00:04:02,342
<i>We will follow four individuals</i>

67
00:04:02,542 --> 00:04:04,811
<i>chasing after their passion.</i>

68
00:04:10,984 --> 00:04:13,620
AUGUST 8, 2018
MUSASHINO FOREST SPORTS PLAZA MAIN ARENA

69
00:04:13,686 --> 00:04:16,155
<i>Three days before the tour's opening day.</i>

70
00:04:18,558 --> 00:04:20,493
SETTING UP
DAY 1

71
00:04:20,560 --> 00:04:25,365
<i>As the stage is being set
by over 150 staff members,</i>

72
00:04:25,765 --> 00:04:29,869
<i>these four individuals take position
with their own goals in mind.</i>

73
00:04:30,937 --> 00:04:34,507
I was hired three months ago.
It's the first time I'm joining a tour.

74
00:04:34,807 --> 00:04:36,409
This is my first day.

75
00:04:36,776 --> 00:04:39,812
{\an8}There's a stage director
and a choreographer,

76
00:04:39,879 --> 00:04:44,183
{\an8}and each has their own image and ideas

77
00:04:44,250 --> 00:04:47,086
{\an8}of how they want the stage
to look for each performance.

78
00:04:47,153 --> 00:04:50,556
Our job is to bring that into fruition.

79
00:04:50,623 --> 00:04:55,295
My job is to care for the needs
of the group members.

80
00:04:55,361 --> 00:04:59,732
I also mark the stage so it's easier for
them to take their positions when dancing.

81
00:04:59,799 --> 00:05:04,103
That way, when it comes time
for the concert,

82
00:05:04,170 --> 00:05:07,473
they can perform exactly the same
as they did during rehearsal.

83
00:05:07,540 --> 00:05:12,178
Each circumstance, location,
and arena has its own characteristics.

84
00:05:12,378 --> 00:05:15,348
So we make sure we adapt
to those differences.

85
00:05:15,415 --> 00:05:16,316
STAGE FACILITATOR

86
00:05:16,382 --> 00:05:19,352
<i>The stage facilitator team,
to which Ueda belongs,</i>

87
00:05:19,419 --> 00:05:22,755
<i>is in charge of everything from
preparation to dismantling.</i>

88
00:05:22,822 --> 00:05:26,492
<i>Their main role is to make sure
the concert goes on without a hitch.</i>

89
00:05:27,860 --> 00:05:29,595
{\an8}<i>With the stage manager in the lead,</i>

90
00:05:29,662 --> 00:05:32,165
{\an8}<i>the team is made up of ten members.</i>

91
00:05:32,231 --> 00:05:35,902
{\an8}<i>Ueda is the newest member,
so he must listen to his seniors</i>

92
00:05:35,968 --> 00:05:39,939
{\an8}<i>and do everything from running errands
to assisting stage production.</i>

93
00:05:42,442 --> 00:05:45,311
<i>What is the difficult part of being
a stage facilitator?</i>

94
00:05:47,013 --> 00:05:48,581
Can you come here for a second?

95
00:05:48,848 --> 00:05:54,220
From building the stage to overseeing
the concert and then dismantling,

96
00:05:54,287 --> 00:05:58,024
the most important thing
is safety management.

97
00:05:58,558 --> 00:05:59,826
That includes the way we work,

98
00:05:59,892 --> 00:06:04,097
and also making sure
there are no problems with the equipment.

99
00:06:04,163 --> 00:06:07,734
We're also responsible
for time management.

100
00:06:08,067 --> 00:06:10,570
As for the actual day of the concert,

101
00:06:10,636 --> 00:06:14,207
we're in charge of the moving props
and the placement of each member.

102
00:06:14,440 --> 00:06:17,276
We also help to connect
the various sections.

103
00:06:17,343 --> 00:06:20,313
As stage crew,
we take the stage director's image

104
00:06:20,380 --> 00:06:24,817
and try to figure out which sections
can take on certain responsibilities,

105
00:06:24,884 --> 00:06:29,989
and together we discuss
how we can bring that image to life.

106
00:06:30,056 --> 00:06:32,759
That's our main role.

107
00:06:32,959 --> 00:06:35,361
{\an8}Have the lighting crew do
that part all at once.

108
00:06:35,428 --> 00:06:38,064
{\an8}All the cables here will be the same,

109
00:06:38,131 --> 00:06:39,766
{\an8}so gather it to that side.

110
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:42,168
{\an8}Gather it together once it's done,

111
00:06:42,235 --> 00:06:44,137
{\an8}and that will connect the lighting.

112
00:06:44,203 --> 00:06:47,807
{\an8}Once you finish checking it,
lift it up and do this area.

113
00:06:49,709 --> 00:06:52,078
-Can you do it?
-Yes.

114
00:06:52,145 --> 00:06:53,946
They're all placed over there.

115
00:06:54,414 --> 00:06:59,519
<i>Even though Ueda is new to this field,
he must remember all the technical terms.</i>

116
00:07:02,288 --> 00:07:05,925
More than the terminology,
it's difficult to keep up with the pace.

117
00:07:06,225 --> 00:07:08,094
It's very fast-paced,

118
00:07:08,261 --> 00:07:11,264
so I have a hard time catching up
and understanding.

119
00:07:13,399 --> 00:07:14,967
I just have to get used to it.

120
00:07:15,668 --> 00:07:19,138
I have to do my best.
I can't slow down the team.

121
00:07:21,574 --> 00:07:25,645
<i>Why did Ueda choose to become
a stage facilitator?</i>

122
00:07:26,446 --> 00:07:28,214
The main reason is,

123
00:07:28,815 --> 00:07:34,887
when I would hear the audience cheering
and having a good time during a concert,

124
00:07:35,087 --> 00:07:40,927
I thought it would be nice to create
something like that as part of my job.

125
00:07:40,993 --> 00:07:42,361
It looked cool.

126
00:07:43,196 --> 00:07:45,498
This is my first tour.

127
00:07:48,234 --> 00:07:50,002
I'm so anxious.

128
00:07:53,272 --> 00:07:54,707
<i>"Full of anxiety."</i>

129
00:07:55,208 --> 00:07:56,776
<i>True to those words,</i>

130
00:07:56,843 --> 00:08:00,079
<i>stage facilitators receive requests
from various departments,</i>

131
00:08:00,146 --> 00:08:02,315
<i>so they must deal with trouble every day.</i>

132
00:08:03,015 --> 00:08:06,152
<i>Each time, they must assess
the situation accurately.</i>

133
00:08:06,219 --> 00:08:09,489
<i>In other words,
it requires resourcefulness.</i>

134
00:08:14,961 --> 00:08:18,965
<i>At two in the afternoon,
a team of women arrive on site.</i>

135
00:08:19,732 --> 00:08:23,135
<i>It's the special effects team,
and this woman is one of its members.</i>

136
00:08:24,237 --> 00:08:26,539
{\an8}My name is Michiru Yabe. I'm 21 years old.

137
00:08:27,607 --> 00:08:30,009
{\an8}This is my second year on the job.

138
00:08:30,309 --> 00:08:32,778
{\an8}I belong to the section

139
00:08:32,845 --> 00:08:36,182
{\an8}called special effects.

140
00:08:37,049 --> 00:08:40,019
{\an8}<i>Their role is to brightly
light up the stage.</i>

141
00:08:40,653 --> 00:08:44,290
What we're using this time
is called a scroller.

142
00:08:44,357 --> 00:08:51,030
It's a device that hangs up above
and scatters gold and silver confetti.

143
00:08:51,230 --> 00:08:55,334
{\an8}We also use theatrical smoke,

144
00:08:55,735 --> 00:08:59,405
{\an8}and sparklers
which shoot sparks into the air.

145
00:08:59,472 --> 00:09:01,874
There's also a piece of equipment
called a color flame

146
00:09:01,941 --> 00:09:06,279
that shoots out green, blue
and red flames.

147
00:09:06,345 --> 00:09:08,447
We also use silver streamers.

148
00:09:08,514 --> 00:09:11,517
Our job includes all of those
stage productions.

149
00:09:13,019 --> 00:09:17,557
<i>This job involves stage production,
so at first glance it may seem flashy,</i>

150
00:09:17,790 --> 00:09:20,226
<i>but it's a series of
slow and steady tasks.</i>

151
00:09:22,028 --> 00:09:24,564
We draw up the cables,

152
00:09:24,630 --> 00:09:27,833
{\an8}and we also set up the address codes
that are necessary

153
00:09:27,900 --> 00:09:31,037
{\an8}to operate these pieces of equipment.

154
00:09:32,438 --> 00:09:34,874
<i>One misprinted number</i>

155
00:09:34,941 --> 00:09:36,709
<i>can ruin the entire production.</i>

156
00:09:38,945 --> 00:09:42,315
{\an8}<i>Nikami, her senior, is also on the team,</i>

157
00:09:42,448 --> 00:09:44,216
{\an8}<i>but everyone else is support staff.</i>

158
00:09:45,952 --> 00:09:47,887
<i>She doesn't have much strength,</i>

159
00:09:48,120 --> 00:09:51,457
<i>but she must carry heavy equipment
by herself.</i>

160
00:09:52,124 --> 00:09:53,159
SPECIAL EFFECTS
ASAKI NIKAMI

161
00:09:53,225 --> 00:09:55,361
At first, you're like Yabe
and don't have much strength.

162
00:09:55,428 --> 00:09:58,798
But you build muscle over time.

163
00:10:00,433 --> 00:10:03,302
We have to be as strong as the boys.

164
00:10:07,440 --> 00:10:11,243
<i>"We have to be as strong as the boys."
That's what Nikami says.</i>

165
00:10:11,744 --> 00:10:15,414
<i>Why did Yabe choose a job
that requires hard labor?</i>

166
00:10:16,849 --> 00:10:20,386
I've always played the piano
and wind instruments,

167
00:10:20,453 --> 00:10:25,658
so ever since I was young
my dream was to work with music.

168
00:10:25,725 --> 00:10:31,831
The first time I went to a concert,
the atmosphere left a big impact on me,

169
00:10:32,098 --> 00:10:36,869
and it made me want to be
part of this field of work.

170
00:10:36,936 --> 00:10:40,139
Special effects like the flames and
silver streamers at the end of the show

171
00:10:40,206 --> 00:10:42,875
made a strong impression on me.

172
00:10:43,175 --> 00:10:45,645
That's what made me want to be part of

173
00:10:46,145 --> 00:10:47,546
the special effects team.

174
00:10:49,215 --> 00:10:51,050
<i>This is the world she's always admired.</i>

175
00:10:51,751 --> 00:10:52,585
<i>But...</i>

176
00:10:52,818 --> 00:10:55,621
<i>these women are about to face a setback</i>

177
00:10:55,788 --> 00:10:57,990
<i>that will crush their high spirits.</i>

178
00:11:01,394 --> 00:11:02,428
<i>At four in the afternoon,</i>

179
00:11:02,495 --> 00:11:06,298
<i>we can see a man helping
the sound team carry in their equipment.</i>

180
00:11:09,001 --> 00:11:13,139
{\an8}My name is Takuma Kuramochi.
I turn 23 this year.

181
00:11:13,205 --> 00:11:16,208
{\an8}I believe this is my third year.

182
00:11:16,409 --> 00:11:18,844
{\an8}During the concert, the PA is in charge of

183
00:11:18,911 --> 00:11:22,715
{\an8}the sound that comes from the speakers.

184
00:11:22,782 --> 00:11:25,317
{\an8}The sound that comes through the speakers

185
00:11:25,384 --> 00:11:28,988
{\an8}is picked up by microphones
or made on the computer.

186
00:11:29,055 --> 00:11:31,791
{\an8}There are various methods,
but the main role

187
00:11:32,124 --> 00:11:33,926
{\an8}of a PA is to create sound.

188
00:11:35,094 --> 00:11:36,629
<i>For the first time ever,</i>

189
00:11:36,696 --> 00:11:40,499
<i>Kuramochi has been assigned
the position as stage chief.</i>

190
00:11:41,133 --> 00:11:42,601
<i>It's a heavy responsibility.</i>

191
00:11:43,235 --> 00:11:46,772
During the concert,
we have to give and receive the mics.

192
00:11:46,839 --> 00:11:51,377
There are also ear monitors
that we have to put on and take off.

193
00:11:51,444 --> 00:11:55,281
So, during the rehearsal
and the actual performance,

194
00:11:55,347 --> 00:11:58,617
our main job is to personally attach
the equipment on the members

195
00:11:58,684 --> 00:12:00,786
and collect them when they're done.

196
00:12:01,854 --> 00:12:05,357
<i>Passing the audio equipment to each artist</i>

197
00:12:05,791 --> 00:12:08,027
<i>may sound easy,</i>

198
00:12:08,260 --> 00:12:11,597
<i>but unless they are aware
of the artist's every move,</i>

199
00:12:11,764 --> 00:12:13,799
<i>it could end up causing a delay.</i>

200
00:12:17,436 --> 00:12:20,639
Today, we did something new
and put lights on the speakers.

201
00:12:20,706 --> 00:12:24,310
So, it took a little longer than usual.
We had to wait a bit,

202
00:12:24,376 --> 00:12:27,346
then add the lights,
then connect the speaker.

203
00:12:27,713 --> 00:12:30,583
It wasn't our usual day,
but it went smoothly.

204
00:12:30,649 --> 00:12:33,652
I'm still a newbie, but...

205
00:12:34,620 --> 00:12:37,890
as I watch the concerts,
I notice that there are times

206
00:12:37,957 --> 00:12:40,960
when the audience is excited,
and times when they're moved.

207
00:12:41,026 --> 00:12:45,064
These concerts provide
many emotional moments,

208
00:12:45,131 --> 00:12:47,066
so I don't want to get in the way of that.

209
00:12:47,199 --> 00:12:50,436
When they're supposed to feel moved,
the sound should convey those feelings,

210
00:12:50,503 --> 00:12:54,540
and when it's a more exciting part,
the sound should give them energy.

211
00:12:55,174 --> 00:12:56,909
In other words,

212
00:12:58,344 --> 00:13:00,513
I think this job requires us to make sure

213
00:13:00,746 --> 00:13:02,381
that nothing feels out of place.

214
00:13:02,448 --> 00:13:03,716
5 P.M.

215
00:13:03,783 --> 00:13:05,417
<i>One hour later,</i>

216
00:13:05,751 --> 00:13:09,488
<i>the special mechanics team begin
to carry in their equipment.</i>

217
00:13:10,055 --> 00:13:12,391
{\an8}My name is Shoichiro Fukuda.
I'm 24 years old.

218
00:13:12,825 --> 00:13:15,094
{\an8}This is my second year.

219
00:13:16,362 --> 00:13:19,799
<i>Not many people have heard
of "special mechanics."</i>

220
00:13:20,199 --> 00:13:22,268
<i>This team is responsible for creating</i>

221
00:13:22,334 --> 00:13:25,805
<i>a stage that goes up and down,
and rotates around.</i>

222
00:13:26,605 --> 00:13:29,842
<i>This shifting stage is a big attraction</i>

223
00:13:29,909 --> 00:13:31,644
<i>for the concert this time.</i>

224
00:13:35,247 --> 00:13:38,350
<i>As a second-year employee,
Fukuda's role is...</i>

225
00:13:40,686 --> 00:13:43,122
Within my team right now,

226
00:13:43,389 --> 00:13:45,291
I hold the lowest position.

227
00:13:45,357 --> 00:13:48,260
So, I mainly do wiring and connect cables

228
00:13:48,694 --> 00:13:51,463
so that everything works properly.

229
00:13:52,531 --> 00:13:55,534
<i>This time, he has been placed
in charge of operating</i>

230
00:13:55,601 --> 00:14:00,105
<i>one of the apparatuses called a lifter
